      {
        "id": 2311993,
        "name": "N@th@n V@nd\u20acrgrift",
        "username": "Nathan_V",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/f04885/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2017-12-08T16:23:29.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Martin Steinley\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n Martin Steinley:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"jcoley3\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/jcoley3/48/507_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> jcoley3:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This is the best producer of White Burgundy I can think of that is mostly unknown here \u2026 especially the Puligny village wine.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Jim, I fully agree with both of these sentiments.  I believe that the general consensus is that J. Carillon consistenly makes the most complete Puligny-Montrachet village wine, but I would argue that Bachelet-Monnot\u2019s version is at least on par.  As good as the 1er crus are, the Puligny-Montrachet village wine is so good that it becomes difficult to justify paying to move up.  The 2014 version is a laser.</p>\n<p>Disclaimer: if not already clear, I sell Bachelet-Monnot.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Carillon has previously been my go to Puligny, but Bachelet-Monnot might have edged them or are at least on par, as you say, and are more readily available to me in my market.</p>",
